things tend to go in cycles. And it's sort of like 
education, you know, we use phonics and then it's

25:17.101 --> 25:22.126
whatever, whatever, whatever. So I don't take 
short-term fluctuations too seriously, and I

25:22.546 --> 25:30.833
think under the last 20, 25 years with NASA and all 
the way... direct missions that the planetary

25:31.471 --> 25:39.243
astronomy may have gotten the lion's share of 
something, and if it goes back the other way, so

25:31.471 --> 25:39.243
what? What's the state of planetary astronomy 
today? Plus, minus, zero? I still think it's a

25:46.293 --> 25:47.375
plus.

25:50.820 --> 25:57.630
And keeping it a plus, in my view, depends on... 
Three things. Continued vitality at the young

25:58.701 --> 26:02.444
investigator level. In other words, enough funds 
to keep a crop

26:02.905 --> 26:12.313
of fresh blood, fresh ideas coming into the field. 
The development, that's one. Two is the

26:15.496 --> 26:21.862
development of good ground-based capabilities 
for observations of planets. And the third is

26:21.922 --> 26:27.347
keeping a reasonable semblance of the space 
program going. Of the three, I worry most about the

26:28.087 --> 26:31.391
last one, number three. But they're all 
intertwined at a rather good level. And so even as

26:38.418 --> 26:44.425
we speak, again, we have Galileo and Mars 
Observer. And so my big question is, where is the

26:45.206 --> 26:49.831
next planetary mission coming from? Will it be the 
Discovery series? Will it be a larger mission,

26:52.634 --> 26:57.840
whatever?

26:58.428 --> 27:04.994
In the last 30 years since NASI got into business, 
the taxpayers have spent a lot of money on

26:58.428 --> 27:04.994
planetary astronomy. What do you think they've 
gotten back from it? I think they got a lot of

27:09.899 --> 27:11.160
excitement. I frankly think that that money, 
generally speaking, has been well spent and that

27:11.260 --> 27:25.594
enough has come of it that is straightforward and 
reasonably simple to understand. You don't need

27:26.535 --> 27:27.996
to be... and a professional astronomer to look at 
an image of a planet at a new resolution or a new

27:29.292 --> 27:38.300
wavelength and see there's brand new stuff going 
on there. I find that, again, when I talk to people

27:39.441 --> 27:54.834
in a public type, you know, the Kiwanis Club, ARP is 
one of my, they're desperate always for programs

27:39.441 --> 27:54.834
where I live, so they keep calling me up, that the 
people appreciate what is being done. I don't

27:54.854 --> 27:57.797
think that when people hear that the NASA budget is 
1% of the federal budget, that they consider that

27:58.233 --> 28:05.429
ill-spent at all? Most people think it's 10% or 
15%, incidentally, which is not true. But again,

28:10.901 --> 28:14.048
perception is the problem here. Let's get a 
particular case now. The University of Colorado

28:16.930 --> 28:22.418
