28:30.809 --> 28:40.543
what was then the physics department. I mean, 
people like Bill Rentsch, doing

28:43.019 --> 28:50.929
spectroscopy of first the sun and other solar 
system objects from rockets. And this has gone on

28:52.150 --> 29:01.682
through the years, and I think one of the other 
important things was Charlie Barth coming to the

28:52.150 --> 29:01.682
University of Colorado. It has then been 
formulated as a goal of the university to be one of

29:01.702 --> 29:10.613
the preeminent centers of space research in the 
country. So I think it started right after World

29:11.774 --> 29:17.220
War II with rockets, mostly launched from White 
Sands. And then it has developed into the more

29:18.322 --> 29:23.127
ambitious programs, the missions to planets. And 
one of the major OSO 8 experiments was at the

29:24.449 --> 29:34.541
University of Colorado.

29:37.444 --> 29:38.906
So I think that pretty much does it. Now, of course, 
we're a major force in the industry. We have a major

29:42.258 --> 29:45.262
new building where we build the instruments. And 
one of our new instruments is one Larry Esposito is

29:46.805 --> 29:52.392
building for Cassini. Mission to Saturn, 
studying rings and everything else. So he's

29:57.899 --> 29:59.822
standing pretty good with the administration.

30:02.185 --> 30:03.266
Not sure what that means. We win our share of the 
competitions, which is the way all these things

30:08.626 --> 30:18.636
are selected, and we have areas of 
world-recognized expertise, detectors,

30:08.626 --> 30:18.636
systems, et cetera. Just out of curiosity, what 
percentage of undergrad students actually get

30:20.598 --> 30:28.366
any exposure to astronomy? I can't, well, first 
