34:03.495 --> 34:06.440
What happened in planetary astronomy? Well, 
missions got more and more complex and more and

34:07.741 --> 34:14.792
more expensive, and I guess Viking was the 
ultimate one. And then what happened? Did the

34:16.815 --> 34:25.427
money just dry up, or did people say, wait a minute, 
the next mission's going to cost the gross

34:16.815 --> 34:25.427
national product, or what actually happened?

34:25.447 --> 34:27.390
Hard to say in detail, but To the human nature, 
everything tends to escalate in expense and

34:28.180 --> 34:34.449
complexity. You know, Toyotas and Nissans or 
Datsuns, as they were then called 10 years ago,

34:35.791 --> 34:45.125
were at the low end of the curve, and they kept 
creeping up and creeping up. And the same human

34:45.165 --> 34:50.112
tendency works in missions. And if a $300 or $400 
million mission was great, well, how about a $2

34:57.610 --> 35:00.535
billion, that one ought to be really fantastic. 
And of course, you reach some kind of law of

35:00.555 --> 35:11.654
diminishing returns where the increment in 
knowledge is not necessarily proportional to the

35:00.555 --> 35:11.654
increment in cost, to put it as delicately as 
possible. So that, coupled with the fact that I am

35:12.595 --> 35:22.993
virtually sure that people in the NASA hierarchy 
are rewarded by the size of their missions or the

35:23.648 --> 35:27.734
amount of the budget that they control. You have a 
built-in escalation mechanism. And I think we see

35:32.741 --> 35:34.904
that in everything that we do. And partly it's a 
technological advance. We know how to do things

35:37.868 --> 35:39.270
better. We don't want to do it the same way we did it 
15 or 20 years ago. And partially it's the tendency

35:43.196 --> 35:51.748
towards complexity and bureaucracy and all the 
other little nummies that we have come to love and

35:43.196 --> 35:51.748
know. Now let's go back to the late unpleasantness 
